    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's get back to the biochemistry.\n\nWhen lactic acid accumulates in the muscles, it triggers a series of biochemical reactions that ultimately lead to the activation of pain receptors. The lactic acid itself doesn't directly trigger pain, but it does contribute to the development of acidosis, which is a decrease in blood pH.\n\nAs the lactic acid builds up, it disrupts the normal functioning of the muscle cells, leading to an increase in the production of pro-inflammatory mediators, such as bradykinin and histamine. These molecules bind to specific receptors on the surface of pain receptors, called nociceptors, and activate them.\n\nThe nociceptors are specialized nerve endings that detect changes in the chemical composition of the muscle tissue. When the lactic acid and other pro-inflammatory mediators bind to these receptors, they trigger a signaling cascade that ultimately leads to the transmission of pain signals to the brain.\n\nThink of it like a goblin's trap - the lactic acid is the bait, and the pain receptors are the trigger that sets off the alarm. The more intense the exercise, the more lactic acid is produced, and the more likely it is that",
